## 3. CAMERA SYSTEM

### CamKF type and useCam hook

```ts
interface CamKF { f: number; cx: number; cy: number; zoom: number }

function useCam(kfs: CamKF[], frame: number, fps: number) {
  if (frame <= kfs[0].f) return kfs[0];
  if (frame >= kfs[kfs.length - 1].f) return kfs[kfs.length - 1];
  for (let i = 0; i < kfs.length - 1; i++) {
    const a = kfs[i], b = kfs[i + 1];
    if (frame >= a.f && frame < b.f) {
      const s = spring({
        frame: frame - a.f, fps,
        config: { damping: 26, stiffness: 160, mass: 1 },
        durationInFrames: Math.max(b.f - a.f, 1),
      });
      return {
        cx: interpolate(s, [0, 1], [a.cx, b.cx]),
        cy: interpolate(s, [0, 1], [a.cy, b.cy]),
        zoom: interpolate(s, [0, 1], [a.zoom, b.zoom]),
      };
    }
  }
  return kfs[kfs.length - 1];
}
```

### Camera keyframe array — hold frames ensure spring settles

```ts
// Rule: duplicate a keyframe ~18 frames before the next move to create a "hold"
// The spring needs ~18 frames to settle; triggering the next move too early causes blending artifacts.
const CAMERA_KFS: CamKF[] = [
  { f: 0,   cx: 960,  cy: 540, zoom: 1.0 },  // full view
  { f: 120, cx: 960,  cy: 540, zoom: 1.0 },  // hold — start moving at 120
  { f: 160, cx: 1188, cy: 462, zoom: 2.5 },  // arrive at target (spring settles ~138)
  { f: 210, cx: 1188, cy: 462, zoom: 2.5 },  // hold — keep zoom before next move
  { f: 250, cx: 960,  cy: 540, zoom: 1.0 },  // return to full view
  { f: 400, cx: 960,  cy: 540, zoom: 1.0 },  // hold to end
];
```

### Camera layer in JSX — apply exactly this

```tsx
// In the main composition:
const cam = useCam(CAMERA_KFS, frame, fps);

<div style={{
  position: "absolute", inset: 0,
  transformOrigin: "50% 50%",
  transform: `translate(${-(cam.cx - 960) * cam.zoom}px, ${-(cam.cy - 540) * cam.zoom}px) scale(${cam.zoom})`,
}}>
  {/* All UI goes here — this is world space */}
  <div style={{ display: "flex", height: 1080, width: 1920 }}>
    <Sidebar />
    <MainContent />
  </div>
  {/* Panels that need to zoom with the camera also go here */}
  {frame >= TL.panelOpen && <SidePanel frame={frame} />}
</div>

{/* Screen-space elements go OUTSIDE the camera div */}
<Cursor frame={frame} />
{frame >= TL.cta && <CalloutOverlay frame={frame} startAt={TL.cta} fps={fps} />}
```

### How to calculate camera target coordinates

For an element at column percentage X of a 1664px content area (1920 - 256px sidebar):
- World X = 256 + (colPct * 1664)
- World Y = measured from top of 1080px canvas (header ~80px, content starts ~80px)

Example: "Statut payeur" column at 51–61% of content area → cx = 256 + 0.56 × 1664 ≈ 1188

