## 14. CIRCULAR CURSOR + RIPPLE (preferred click cursor)

Use this instead of the SVG arrow cursor for product demos. The ripple ring clearly signals a click without an arrow distracting from the UI.

**Dual-visibility cursor (visible on both white cards and dark navy background):**
- Dot: `background: T.navy` (`#0E1029`) — dark, visible on white
- Halo: `box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px rgba(255,255,255,0.90)` — white ring, visible on dark
- Ripple ring: `border: 2px solid T.navy` — expands outward on click

This combination works on any surface: dark dot contrasts on light, white halo contrasts on dark. Never use a pure white dot (invisible on light cards).

```tsx
// Waypoints — spring-interpolated path
interface WP { f: number; x: number; y: number }

// IMPORTANT: This is a plain function, NOT a React hook.
// Do NOT prefix with "use" — calling it conditionally (e.g. inside if blocks) would
// violate React's rules of hooks if it were named useCursorPos.
function getCursorPos(wps: WP[], frame: number, fps: number) {
  if (frame <= wps[0].f) return { x: wps[0].x, y: wps[0].y };
  if (frame >= wps[wps.length - 1].f) return { x: wps[wps.length - 1].x, y: wps[wps.length - 1].y };
  for (let i = 0; i < wps.length - 1; i++) {
    const a = wps[i], b = wps[i + 1];
    if (frame >= a.f && frame < b.f) {
      const s = spring({ frame: frame - a.f, fps, config: { damping: 30, stiffness: 100 } });
      return { x: interpolate(s, [0, 1], [a.x, b.x]), y: interpolate(s, [0, 1], [a.y, b.y]) };
    }
  }
  return { x: wps[wps.length - 1].x, y: wps[wps.length - 1].y };
}

// Define waypoints and click frame in TL
const CURSOR_WPS: WP[] = [
  { f: TL.cursorIn, x: 1480, y: 680 },     // appears off to the side
  { f: TL.cursorAt, x: TARGET_X, y: TARGET_Y }, // glides to target
  { f: TL.dashOut + 20, x: TARGET_X, y: TARGET_Y },
];

function Cursor({ frame, fps }: { frame: number; fps: number }) {
  if (frame < TL.cursorIn || frame > TL.dashOut + 18) return null;

  const pos     = getCursorPos(CURSOR_WPS, frame, fps);
  const o       = fade(frame, TL.cursorIn, 10) * fdOut(frame, TL.dashOut, 14);
  const clickDt = frame - TL.click;
  const isClick = clickDt >= 0 && clickDt <= 22;

  // Dot compresses on click, then returns
  const dotSc = isClick ? 1 - 0.4 * Math.sin((clickDt / 22) * Math.PI) : 1;
  // Ripple ring expands outward and fades
  const ringR = isClick ? interpolate(clickDt, [0, 22], [14, 38], clamp) : 14;
  const ringO = isClick ? interpolate(clickDt, [0, 4, 22], [0, 1, 0], clamp) : 0;

  return (
    <div style={{ position: "absolute", left: 0, top: 0, opacity: o, pointerEvents: "none", zIndex: 300 }}>
      {/* Expanding ripple ring */}
      <div style={{
        position: "absolute",
        left: pos.x - ringR, top: pos.y - ringR,
        width: ringR * 2, height: ringR * 2, borderRadius: "50%",
        border: "2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.85)",
        opacity: ringO,
      }} />
      {/* White dot — compresses on click */}
      <div style={{
        position: "absolute",
        left: pos.x - 10, top: pos.y - 10,
        width: 20, height: 20, borderRadius: "50%",
        background: "#fff",
        boxShadow: "0 0 0 4px rgba(255,255,255,0.22), 0 0 24px rgba(255,255,255,0.55)",
        transform: `scale(${dotSc})`,
        transformOrigin: "center center",
      }} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Calculating click target coordinates in Frame-based mode:**
Trace from the component structure in your scene:
- `paddingTop` of the scene container
- Chip height + gap + headline height + gap + KPI section height + gap = distance to table top
- Table header height + (row index × row height) + (row height / 2) = row center Y
- Column left offset + (column width / 2) = click X

Document these in comments above `CLICK_X` / `CLICK_Y` constants.

