## 20. SEQUENCE-BASED AUDIO SYNC (native Remotion — preferred over ffmpeg)

Per-scene voiceover with frame-accurate sync. Each clip lives in `public/voiceover/[comp]/[scene].mp3`.

```tsx
import { Audio, Sequence, staticFile } from "remotion";
// Audio MUST come from @remotion/media, not remotion
import { Audio } from "@remotion/media";

// In main composition — one <Sequence> per scene clip:
<Sequence from={TL.heroIn}>
  <Audio src={staticFile("voiceover/campagnes/hero.mp3")} />
</Sequence>
<Sequence from={TL.s1In}>
  <Audio
    src={staticFile("voiceover/campagnes/step1.mp3")}
    volume={(f) => interpolate(f, [0, 8], [0, 1], { extrapolateRight: "clamp" })}
  />
</Sequence>
```

**Why `<Sequence>` beats ffmpeg:** Remotion controls the audio frame-for-frame during render. The `from` prop is the exact frame where playback starts — no millisecond approximation, no conversion math.

**Volume callback** — `f` is the local frame (0 = when the audio starts), not the global frame. Use it for fade-in (first 8f) or fade-out.

**Multiple clips layered** — just add more `<Sequence>/<Audio>` pairs. Remotion mixes them automatically.

