## 22. SEQUENCE & SERIES FOR SCENE TIMING

An alternative to manual `if (frame < TL.xxx) return null` guards. Use when scenes are sequential with no complex overlapping.

```tsx
import { Series, Sequence } from "remotion";

// Series — sequential scenes, no overlap. Frame resets to 0 inside each child.
<Series>
  <Series.Sequence durationInFrames={90}>
    <HeroScene />        {/* useCurrentFrame() → 0–89 locally */}
  </Series.Sequence>
  <Series.Sequence offset={-15} durationInFrames={220}>
    {/* Starts 15f before Hero ends — overlap for cross-fade */}
    <Step1Scene />
  </Series.Sequence>
</Series>

// Sequence — delay a single element. Adds premountFor for preloading.
<Sequence from={TL.dashIn} premountFor={30}>
  <DashboardScene />
</Sequence>
```

**Key difference from our manual TL approach:**
- Inside `<Sequence from={90}>`, `useCurrentFrame()` returns `0` at global frame 90, not `90`. All local animation math starts at 0.
- Our current approach (passing `frame` as prop + global TL) is fine for complex multi-element scenes where you need global frame references. Use `<Series>` only for cleanly sequential scenes without internal cross-references to other scene TL frames.

**Always add `premountFor`** to `<Sequence>` — it preloads the component before it becomes visible, preventing pop-in on first render.

